{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478707"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17585"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17585"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.05,0.05,0.66,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71382"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10275"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56860"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8770"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44007"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71382"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent for a routine health check prior to starting school. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. His parent mentions noticing that he sometimes confuses red and green colours when drawing. There is a family history of \u0027colour blindness\u0027 in his maternal uncle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His visual acuity is 6/6 in both eyes. Ishihara plate testing reveals difficulties identifying red-green patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange genetic testing","Prescribe corrective lenses","Repeat testing in six months","Inform school and provide educational support","Refer for urgent ophthalmology assessment"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with features consistent with red-green colour vision deficiency, which is the most common form of colour blindness. The X-linked inheritance pattern is supported by the family history in the maternal uncle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInforming the school and providing educational support\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Colour vision deficiency is not correctable, but awareness among teachers can help ensure appropriate accommodations are made, such as using different teaching methods that don\u0027t rely heavily on colour discrimination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent ophthalmology assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as colour vision deficiency is not progressive and does not affect visual acuity. The child has normal visual acuity and no other concerning eye symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic testing\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely indicated as the diagnosis can be made clinically. The inheritance pattern is well understood, and testing would not change management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorrective lenses\u003C/strong\u003E would not improve colour vision deficiency. While some specialised filters exist, they are not recommended for children and do not correct the underlying deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat testing\u003C/strong\u003E in six months is unnecessary as colour vision deficiency is a stable condition. The Ishihara test is reliable in children of this age, and the family history supports the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EColour vision deficiency affects approximately 8% of males and 0.5% of females due to X-linked inheritance patterns. Early identification allows for appropriate educational support and career guidance, as certain occupations may have specific colour vision requirements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colour vision deficiency affects approximately 1 in 12 males and 1 in 200 females due to X-linked inheritance.","Red-green colour deficiency is the most common form of colour vision deficiency.","Colour vision testing should be performed before school age to identify affected children and implement appropriate educational support."],"references":["Xie JZ, Tarczy-Hornoch K, Lin J, Cotter SA, Torres M, Varma R; Multi-Ethnic Pediatric Eye Disease Study Group. Color vision deficiency in preschool children: the multi-ethnic pediatric eye disease study. Ophthalmology. 2014 Jul;121(7):1469-74. doi: 10.1016/j.ophtha.2014.01.018. Epub 2014 Mar 16. PMID: 24702753; PMCID: PMC4839481."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56860"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17585"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56860"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T09:59:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T10:00:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10275"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71382"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes"